tive to R9-1/4A</td></tr><tr><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">11</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">6-Cl library:4 best variants from Round 10plus R9 1/4A; 2±1 mutationsper gene</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">6-chlorobenzisoxazole;≤1.2-fold relative to Ri0 variants</td></tr><tr><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">12</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">5-Flibrary:7 best variantsfrom Round 11 plus R9 1/4A;2±1 mutations per gene</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">5-fluoro benzisoxazole;≤1.4-fold relative to R11-7/8D</td></tr><tr><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">13</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"> 5-F library:Shuffling of the12 best variantsfrom Round 12</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">5-fluoro benzisoxazole;≤1.4-fold relative to R12-7/1B</td></tr><tr><td colspan="1" rowspan="2">Round#</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="2">Random mutagenesis</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="2">Recombination</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="2"> Oligo spiking</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="2">Substrate;Fold improvement measured with crude lysates+</td></tr><tr></tr><tr><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">14</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"> 5-F library:4 best variantsfrom Round 13; 2±1 mutationsper gene</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">5-fluoro benzisoxazole;≤1.6-fold relative to R13-3/11H</td></tr><tr><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">15</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">5-F library: Shuffling of the18 best variantsfrom Round 14</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">5-fluoro benzisoxazole;≤l.3-fold relative to R14-10/8B</td></tr><tr><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">16</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"> 5-F library:12 best variantsfrom Round 15 plus 3 variantsfrom Round 14; 2±1 mutationsper gene</td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1"></td><td colspan="1" rowspan="1">5-fluoro benzisoxazole;≤1.3-fold relative to R15-6/6C</td></tr></table>

\* In the libraries, the NdeI site in the synthetic gene encoding the designed KE59 protein was replaced by NcoI, which involved insertion of alanine residue after the N-terminus methionine. Mutagenesis level was regulated by varying the template concentration and number of polymerization cycles in the error-prone PCR with mutazyme (Genemorph PCR mutagenesis kit, Stratagene). The number of mutations per gene was estimated by sequencing ${ \sim } 1 0$ clones from the unscreened library, and is indicated in the second column. It should be noted that only a fraction of the obtained diversity $( > 5 , 0 0 0$ different permutations, even at a single amino acid mutation per variant) could be covered by our medium throughput screening (600-2000 variants were screened at each directed evolution round). † Since the expression of KE59 had not reached its maximal level, the apparent improvement in activity was often due to an increase in expression rather than specific activity.

# B. Kinetic analysis of KE59 variants

Enzymatic characterization. For the kinetic characterization, the reactions were started by adding $1 5 0 ~ \mu \mathrm { l }$ of substrate (final concentration - $0 . 1 3 \mathrm { - } 1 . 0 5 ~ \mathrm { m M }$ , or $0 . 0 6 5 { \cdot } 0 . 5 2 5 \mathrm { m M }$ , in $2 5 ~ \mathrm { m M }$ HEPES $\mathrm { p H } ~ 7 . 2 5$ with $1 0 0 \ \mathrm { m M \ N a C l } )$ , to $5 0 \mu \mathrm { l }$ of enzyme in storage buffer, as previously described (2, 3).

$p H \cdot$ -rate profile. $\mathbf { k } _ { \mathrm { c a t } }$ and $\mathrm { K } _ { \mathrm { m } }$ values were determined with 5-nitrobenzisoxazole at $\mathrm { p H } ~ 5 \textmd { - }$ 8.5 for KE59 variants R2-4/3D, R4-5/11B, R8-2/7A, R9-1/4A, and R13-3/11H (2, 3). Initial velocities $\left( \mathbf { v } _ { 0 } \right)$ were determined at eight different substrate concentrations (0.13- $1 . 0 5 ~ \mathrm { m M }$ or $0 . 0 6 5 { \cdot } 0 . 5 2 5 \mathrm { m M } )$ . The buffers used (at $5 0 ~ \mathrm { m M }$ ) were: Citrate (pH 5.0-5.5), MES $\mathrm { ( p H ~ } 5 . 5 – 6 . 5 )$ , and Bis-tris propane $\mathrm { ( p H ~ 6 . 5  – 8 . 0 ) }$ at $5 0 ~ \mathrm { m M }$ . At $\mathrm { p H } 5 . 5$ and 6.5, the activity was measured with both relevant buffers. The ionic strength was adjusted to a total of 0.1M with NaCl.

Data analysis. Kinetic parameters $( k _ { c a t } , K _ { M } , k _ { c a t } / K _ { M } )$ were obtained by fitting the data to the Michaelis-Menten equation $[ \mathrm { v } _ { 0 } { = } k _ { c a t } [ \mathrm { E } ] _ { 0 } [ \mathrm { S } ] _ { 0 } / ( [ \mathrm { S } ] _ { 0 } { + } K _ { M } ) ] .$ , using the program Kaleidagraph 5.0. When working with low substrate concentrations, data were fitted to the linear regime of the Michaelis-Menten model $[ \mathrm { v _ { 0 } } \mathrm { = [ S ] _ { 0 } [ E ] _ { 0 } k _ { c a t } / K _ { M } } ]$ , and $\mathrm { k _ { c a t } / K _ { M } }$ was deduced from the slope. All the data presented are the averages of at least three independent experiments, with the standard deviations between the repeated experiments typically being $< 1 0 \%$ .

![](images/f22d727e80b54bf60c641612baf87982ecebc438b31d1a217a3288aa2f71167b.jpg)

Fig. S5. Product formation was monitored with $0 . 2 5 \mathrm { m M }$ 5-nitrobenzisoxazole (A), 0.1mM 5,7- dichlorobenzisoxazole $\mathbf { ( B ) }$ , $0 . 1 \mathrm { m M }$ 6-chlorobenzisoxazole (C) and KE59 variants at various protein concentrations $\mathbf { \eta } ^ { ( \mathbf { D } ) }$ . Also shown is buffer/hydroxide catalyzed decomposition (no enzyme). Multiple turnovers were observed in all the cases, and saturation was observed with activated substrates (5-nitro and 5,7-dichloro benzisoxazoles). In case of less activated substrate (6-chlorobenzisoxazole), saturation was observed with the more active KE59 variants, but not for KE59 from earlier rounds of directed evolution. Possible reasons for this could be protein destabilization and inactivation over the long reaction time and/or product inhibition.

![](images/47c8dc2db92346668d7472288e6e61b8e6dce1ac7f3ce9db351fb55784d26026.jpg)
Fig. S6. Typical Michaelis-Menten plots, shown here for Kemp elimination of 5- nitrobenzisoxazole by KE59 variants R1 7/10H $( \mathbf { A } )$ , R4 5/11B $\mathbf { ( B ) }$ , R9 1/4A (C) and R13 3/11H $\mathbf { \eta } ^ { ( \mathbf { D } ) }$ . Kinetic parameters $( k _ { c a t } , ~ K _ { M } , ~ k _ { c a t } / K _ { M } )$ were obtained by fitting the data to the Michaelis-Menten equation $[ \mathrm { v } _ { 0 } { = } k _ { c a t } [ \mathrm { E } ] _ { 0 } [ \mathrm { S } ] _ { 0 } / ( [ \mathrm { S } ] _ { 0 } { + } K _ { M } ) ] .$ , using the program Kaleidagraph 5.0. In some cases, such as (A), no saturation could be obtained due to limited substrate solubility, and the data were fitted to the linear regime of the Michaelis-Menten model $[ \mathbf { v } _ { 0 } ] =$ $[ \mathrm { S } ] _ { 0 } [ \mathrm { E } ] _ { 0 } \mathbf { k } _ { \mathrm { c a t } } / \mathbf { K } _ { \mathrm { M } } ] .$ , and $\mathrm { k _ { c a t } / K _ { m } }$ was deduced from the slope.

![](images/e11ecbe1b81c1daf597a6478a1ba7d44842df3f180a982705da70b1df2dc7d13.jpg)
Fig. S7. pH-rate profiles of the KE59 variants. A. a plot of $k _ { \mathrm { c a t } }$ versus $\mathsf { p H }$ ; B. $k _ { \mathrm { { c a t } } } / K _ { \mathrm { { m } } }$ versus $\mathrm { p H }$ . The $\mathrm { p H } .$ -rate data $k _ { \mathrm { c a t } }$ and $k _ { \mathrm { { c a t } } } / \mathrm { K } _ { \mathrm { m } }$ values for each $\mathsf { p H }$ value $\left( k _ { \mathrm { c a t } } \right) ^ { \mathrm { H } }$ and $( k _ { \mathrm { { c a t } } } / K _ { \mathrm { { m } } } ) ^ { \mathrm { { H } } } )$ were fitted using the equations $( k _ { \mathrm { c a t } } ) ^ { \mathrm { H } } { = } ( k _ { \mathrm { c a t } } ) ^ { \mathrm { m a x } } \mathrm { x } 1 0 ^ { - \mathrm { p K a } } / ( 1 0 ^ { - \mathrm { p H } } { + } 1 0 ^ { - \mathrm { p K a } } )$ and $( k _ { \mathrm { c a t } } / K _ { \mathrm { m } } ) ^ { \mathrm { H } } { = } ( \ k _ { \mathrm { c a t } } / K _ { \mathrm { m } } ) ^ { \mathrm { m a x } } \mathrm { x } 1 0 ^ { - \mathrm { p K a } } / ( 1 0 ^ { - \mathrm { p H } } { + } 1 0 ^ { - \mathrm { p K a } } )$ ; where $\left( k _ { \mathrm { c a t } } \right) ^ { \mathrm { m a x } }$ and $( k _ { \mathrm { { c a t } } } / K _ { \mathrm { { m } } } ) ^ { \mathrm { { m a x } } }$ are the plateau values of $k _ { \mathrm { c a t } }$ and $k _ { \mathrm { { c a t } } } / K _ { \mathrm { { m } } } ,$ and $\mathsf { p } K _ { \mathsf { a l } }$ is the apparent $\mathrm { p K _ { a } }$ value for the acidic group.

